Radical thought: I believe one can shut the timer off in the settings. I don't mean just pause it but get rid of the little irritant entirely. I sometimes feel a solve is taking longer or moving faster than usual. Sometimes I'm interested by the times people post. But it's basically a big snooze for me. I just like figuring out the puzzles. Simple.

@Steve L

We already know a lot of these people can post blistering times, as well.  We see them on occasion.

I don't consider it gauche.  But I'm the kind that never volunteered my marathon times, unless they were awful by weekend runner standards.

@lucky13

If I were a newbie now, I would ignore the time, too.  Back in the day, ignoring the time was the default setting, since you had to look at your watch before you started, and you did that only if you cared enough.

Wait five years, and you may change your mind.  You also may not, and that's OK, too.

@Heidi

People start paying attention to times when they've already gotten to the point that the solve is not ever in doubt.  It's a way to gauge improvement.  Even if you don't speed solve, a faster time means you're figuring out the clues with less hesitancy and difficulty.

If you're not there yet, you may be some day.  Or you may never care. Either way is fine.

